<font color="#FF0000">HOW DO YOU SAY......THANKS?</font><br>
<tt>Sun Nov 16  2:44:06 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Grateful Grunt:<br><br>
It was not heroism that allows one to hover into intensive enemy fire.. it is the prevailing thought that a brother might not make it home if you don't go and get him!<br><br>
As an old Rotorhead..I am humbled and embarrassed to take praise from the lowest paid, hardest fighting, but certainly most honorable men on the face of the earth..grunts.<br><br>
During an approach into a hot LZ, I would feel my heart go up into my throat..I could hear bullets striking the fuselage and feared that crew or passengers were wounded (and they often were) or that we would all plummet to the ground in a large fireball(which happened on occassions)..on several radios I would hear the frantic radio messages of my friends in trouble..going down or reporting KIA/WIA pilots, crewchiefs and doorgunners. With terror filled eyes, I saw burning aircraft on the ground and dead and wounded infantrymen scattered on the field before me...I saw muzzle flashes from automatic weapons firing at me from the tree lines and felt a consuming fear. I heard my doorgunner and crew chief returning fire or turned to see them hanging lifeless in their harnesses.<br>
Three or four feet before I hit the ground..riflemen, machine gunners, medics, mortar men, radio men, privates, corporals, sergeants, lieutenants, Captains piled out of the cargo hold to engage a dug in enemy force..some lay on the cargo deck in pools of blood and urine never having been given the chance to make the charge.<br>
Always, as I came out.. I thought of those I had left behind.  I was a dog with his tail between his legs..hauling ass from the scene.  Always, I would return with reinforcements..water..ammo.  Everytime there would be the KIAs in body bags or those quickly wrapped in ponchos...  everytime there were those who were wounded..some awake, some not!<br>
Finally, I would pull them all out..either in a slow,quiet shallow victory or frantically extract them under intense fire, when things didn't go well.  I will never forget the empty eyes of the survivors, those that had stared into the jaws of death.<br>
I could never refuse a medivac..regardless of the weather or enemy situation..not because I was heroic but because I was indebted...and was humbled by the unrecorded heroism of many low ranking infantrymen who faced death for me and my country.<br>
As wordy as I am I will never be able to fully convey the appreciation and high regard burned into my mind by the thousands of noble infantrymen who rode with me to the fight...while I flew away to land in a grassey field to hope and pray for them!<br><br>
God Bless You - Gary.... Tom, Paul, James, and Cookie! <br><br>
Thanks - Bob, Art and John for helping everybody!<br><br>
Wish I had something as meaningful as Bro Ron's utility jacket to convey my love and respect.<br><br>
Mustang Two Four - Slicks and Guns<br><br>
P.S.  Thanks Class Lass for the pretty round eyes..thanks Anne for caring.
